I would like to take this opportunity on this Good Friday to recommend this new book by Paul Washer.

“There is simply no way to exaggerate the centrality and preeminence of the gospel. It is not the only message in Christianity, but it is first in rank, dignity, and beauty. It does not supplant the other great truths of Scripture, but it is their

Yesterday marked the 20 year mark that my best friend William Harrell died in a car accident. 

We worked together. We were both young preachers dreaming of laboring together in gospel ministry. He was in my wedding just 6-months earlier. His wife was 10-weeks pregnant with their first child. It was tragic. It hurt a ton. But, our Lord had plans that we didn’t know about. 

In God’s design, we went away to seminary and met a man who my wife eventually introduced to Kerri (William’s widow) and as God would have it, they ended up getting married.

I preached William’s funeral and then a few years later officiated the wedding of Chip Thornton and Kerri Harrell (William’s widow). 

One day we will embrace again in the new heavens and the new earth! We have some catching up to do! 

William Cowper once said that sometimes behind a frowning providence God hides a smiling face. 

True.

At the Midnight Mass on December 24th 1555, Robert Barns took to this pulpit at St Edward’s Church and preached the first Protestant sermon in all of England. 

Barns was one of the men who frequently gathered together at the White Horse Inn pub to discuss theology and Reformation doctrine. Their little group became known as “Little Germany.” The group consisted of men such as Hugh Latimer, Nicholas Ridley, John Rogers, William Tyndale, and Miles Coverdale. 

It was a privilege to speak to our group and to climb into the pulpit of this historic church building on our Reformation tour.
From this building in London, England, the Doctor, D. Martyn Lloyd-Jones labored passionately in preaching God’s Word. #Preaching #martynlloydjones

The life of John Knox was one for the ages. He was a Roman Catholic who became a Reformed pastor. He was taken captive and spent time as a galley slave on a ship. He became friends with John Calvin. He is the founder of the Presbyterian Church in Scotland. He is the originator of Puritanism in England. He was summoned to stand before the Queen to answer for his preaching. He was a prolific author who penned creeds, confessions, and polemical books. He played a big role in the translation and study notes of the 1560 Geneva Bible which became the first study Bible in the history of the world. Yet, to this very day many people have forgotten the great Reformer.
